Chicago And Its Suburbs Pick Enron, ComEd For Power Deals

06/06/2001
Dow Jones Energy Service
(Copyright (c) 2001, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.)

CHICAGO -(Dow Jones)- The City of Chicago and 47 suburban communities have=20
decided to divide new deals for 400 megawatts of power between Enron Corp.=20
(ENE) and local utility Commonwealth Edison Co., Chicago officials said=20
Wednesday.=20
In the largest power purchase agreement in Illinois since the state choose t=
o=20
deregulate the industry in 1997, the local government groups will get 60% of=
=20
their power from Enron and 40% from Exelon Corp.'s (EXC) ComEd. The=20
municipalities use the power for public buildings and public transportation.
"We used our purchasing power as local governments to get the best price we=20
could and at the same time to promote competition in Illinois," Chicago Mayo=
r=20
Richard M. Daley said at a press conference.=20
The government coalition sent out a request for proposals to the state's 13=20
registered electricity providers last summer requesting bids for cheaper=20
power, and also for power that's generated with 20% renewable supplies.=20
Combined, the municipalities currently pay ComEd about $110.6 million a year=
=20
for 400 megawatts of power, most of which comes from nuclear and coal-fired=20
power plants.=20
Chicago announced Monday that the group has picked ComEd to meet the=20
renewable target by providing 80 megawatts of power created with landfill=20
gas, wind and other sources. ComEd will also provide the coalition with=20
another 80 megawatts of power generated with fossil fuel and nuclear plants,=
=20
and Enron will provide the other 240 megawatts. The new contracts are=20
expected to go into effect this year.=20
Terms of the power deals weren't announced, as about 4,000 accounts between=20
municipal agencies and the two power providers must still be ironed out, cit=
y=20
officials said.=20
But the government groups do have a target for savings. Chicago, which uses=20
about 200 megawatts and pays ComEd about $50 million annually for power,=20
expects to save a net $3 million a year through a combination of cheaper=20
power from Enron and more expensive renewable power from ComEd. Once all the=
=20
accounting is completed, it's likely the municipal groups will save up to $5=
=20
million in total each year, the city estimates.=20
"Enron gave us the most competitive price," Daley said.

