INDIA: Enron's Dabhol takes Indian regulator to court.

06/06/2001
Reuters English News Service
(C) Reuters Limited 2001.

BOMBAY, June 6 (Reuters) - Enron's Dabhol Power Company (DPC) has challenged=
=20
the jurisdiction of a local regulatory body in trying to resolve a dispute=20
between the company and an Indian state utility that has threatened nearly $=
3=20
billion worth of foreign investment, an industry source said on Wednesday.=20
Dabhol, owned 65 percent by Houston-based Enron , filed a petition on=20
Wednesday before the Bombay high court questioning the jurisdiction of the=20
Maharashtra State Electricity Regulatory Commission (MERC), the source added=
=2E
MERC, which was not immediately available to comment, last week intervened i=
n=20
the dispute by granting interim relief to the utility.=20
A Dabhol spokesman declined to comment.=20
MERC, which is responsible for electricity regulation in Maharashtra, had=20
intervened in the dispute last week by restraining Dabhol from certain=20
actions.=20
It asked the company, which is fighting a legal case against MSEB, from=20
proceeding against the utility in the International Court of Arbitration in=20
London. The regulator also asked the company not to activate a special bank=20
account which is crucial for Dabhol to continue work on the project's second=
=20
phase.=20
Dabhol's 2,184 MW power project on India's western coast is being set up in=20
two phases. The first phase of 740 MW is already supplying power to MSEB,=20
while the second phase of 1,444 MW is expected to be operational soon.=20
Dabhol had stated before the Commission that it does not recognise its=20
authority to intervene in the dispute. As per the 1995 agreemnt with MSEB,=20
all disputes are to be resolved through international arbitratration.=20
The source said Wednesday's petiton before the Bombay high court questions=20
MERC's role but did not reveal any other details. The Press Trust of India=20
said the petiton would come up for hearing on June 11.=20
The move comes amidst an escalating row between between Dabhol and the=20
Maharashtra State Electricity Board (MSEB), over payment defaults and high=20
tariffs.=20
MSEB began defaulting on its payments six months ago to Dabhol saying that=20
its power was too costly. It also cancelled its purchases and said it would=20
be unable to lift output from the second phase.=20
Dabhol filed for arbitration and issued a preliminary notice to cancel its=20
contract with MSEB.=20
The dispute has already affected India's image among foreign investors and=20
global credit rating agency Moody's Investor Services said last week the=20
dispute has raised concerns over whether India would be able to fulfill its=20
contractual obgligations.=20
The dispute is also affecting foreign and local lenders, who have been=20
meeting for two days in Singapore to discuss the fate of the project. They=20
are slated to continue discussions on Thursday.=20
Foreign lenders want to cancel their loans worth around $600 million to the=20
project while the local lenders are urging them against it.=20
A senior banking official told Reuters that no decision was taken on=20
Wednesday regarding the cancellation of loans. It will most probably be=20
decided on Thursday when the foregin lenders confer amongst themselves..=20
The Indian lenders who participated in the meeting for two days are returnin=
g=20
on Wednesday, he added.=20
Meanwhile, the Indian Prime Minister, Atal Behari Vajpayee, said on Wednesda=
y=20
that he was hopeful of a solution to the dispute.=20
"The Enron issue is on the way to being solved. I am confident the governmen=
t=20
of Maharashtra and Enron will together sort out the problem," he told=20
reporters in Bombay. But he expressed doubts whether other Indian states wil=
l=20
be able to afford the cost.=20
"Yes, that is a problem and we are trying to solve it. The other states will=
=20
also have the same problem that the Maharashtra government is facing. What=20
will they do with such expensive power?," he asked. ($1=3D46.97 Indian rupee=
s).

