USA: ANALYSIS-LNG gets new look as way to ease US energy woes.
By Manuela Badawy

06/06/2001
Reuters English News Service
(C) Reuters Limited 2001.

NEW YORK, June 6 (Reuters) - With blackouts in California a stark example of=
=20
what is at stake if the United States runs short of natural gas, liquefied=20
natural gas, or LNG, is getting a new look as a means to solve a growing U.S=
=2E=20
energy crisis.=20
While natural gas has been increasingly embraced in the United States for it=
s=20
environmental virtues - it burns more cleanly than oil or coal and emits=20
fewer greenhouse gases - LNG has been all but abandoned due to poor economic=
s=20
and fears that transporting it safely by ship is not worth the risk.
But with gas prices at historically high levels amid forecasts that U.S. gas=
=20
demand is beginning to outpace domestic supplies, LNG suddenly looks=20
financially viable, and the LNG industry insists improved technologies have=20
minimized risks.=20
Some analysts are even saying LNG's share of the U.S. gas market could tripl=
e=20
to more than 10 percent over the next half decade as oil companies like El=20
Paso Corp., Texaco Inc. and BP set plans to build about 10 new plants in and=
=20
near the United States to process LNG. Those 10 would join four existing=20
plants, two of which have been out of operation for years.=20
"Significant new investment in LNG to serve U.S. markets will probably be=20
attractive if long-term average gas prices in Gulf Coast producing areas are=
=20
$3.25 per mmBtu or higher," said Howard Gruenspecht of Resources for the=20
Future, a Washington think tank. Natural gas prices are now at about $4 per=20
million British thermal units (mmBtu), down from an all-time high over $10=20
per mmBtu last December.=20
LNG is natural gas in a highly compressed, super-cold form that enables it t=
o=20
be transported in special tankers much like crude oil.=20
Safety concerns aside, spurring LNG imports is probably the quickest way=20
among a number of options to prevent energy shortages like those in=20
California from spreading. LNG would also give gas producers around the worl=
d=20
access to the huge U.S. market which, in this decade, could grow by 30=20
percent.=20
But those safety concerns remain in sharp focus, as citizens continue to=20
raise not-in-my-backyard-type objections to LNG development, making winning=20
regulatory approval extremely difficult.=20
TEXACO MAY HAVE THE ANSWER=20
LNG's public relations problem began with a 1944 accident in Cleveland=20
involving leaking tanks that killed 128 people. The industry never quite got=
=20
over that, and 38 more deaths in the 1970s from two East Coast LNG explosion=
s=20
all but sealed LNG's star-crossed fate.=20
LNG's compressed, super-cold form requires careful handling, particularly=20
when it is brought back to normal atmospheric temperatures and pressures.=20
But analysts say the LNG industry has come a long way on safety, particularl=
y=20
of the tanks themselves, and risks are lower than they have ever been.=20
"The LNG market makes for a good science fiction story because it's this=20
cryogenic liquid, but the fact of the matter is that it's a far safer fuel=20
than a lot of the combustible hydrocarbons," said Bob Nimocks, president of=20
energy consulting firm Zeus Development Corp.=20
Texaco thinks it may have the solution to the not-in-my-backyard obstacle=20
that dogs LNG development with plans to build an offshore LNG plant off the=20
coast of Louisiana in the Gulf of Mexico.=20
Putting a plant offshore, far from towns and cities, would not only=20
neutralize the so-called NIMBY factor, it would also speed regulatory=20
approvals since many of the risks regulators weigh so carefully for=20
land-based plants do not exist in the Gulf.=20
"The possibility of constructing the terminal offshore may allow it to be=20
built without incurring local citizen objection and it would be less=20
expensive," Nimocks said.=20
Double-walled tankers would offload the natural gas in a liquid state into=20
low-pressure storage tanks. After the LNG is stored, it would then be=20
"vaporized" into natural gas, which can then be transported by pipeline to=20
shore.=20
Texaco's terminal, which would be large by industry standards, would have an=
=20
initial capacity of 1 billion cubic feet (bcf) of natural gas per day, or=20
enough gas to power upward of 6 million single-family homes.=20
"You would need three terminals of this size running full-time to provide=20
just 1 trillion cubic feet (tcf) of annual LNG import capacity," Gruenspecht=
=20
said.=20
Total U.S. import capacity of LNG is about 1.0 tcf per year, or about 4=20
percent of U.S. gas consumption, though actual LNG imports in 2001 will be=20
less than half of that because the two mothballed terminals are only now in=20
the process of being reopened.=20
ALL IN PERSPECTIVE=20
If all the new projects being contemplated do materialize, LNG may feed 8=20
percent to 12 percent of the total U.S. gas market by 2007.=20
Last year, U.S. demand for natural gas was about 22.7 tcf and is projected t=
o=20
increase up to 12 tcf during the next 10 years as utilities lean more heavil=
y=20
on gas to fire electricity generators, analysts said. In other words, gas no=
w=20
makes up 24 percent of U.S. energy use, but by 2020 that percentage will ris=
e=20
to 36.5 percent.=20
As long as natural gas prices stay above the $3.50/$4.00 per mmBtu range, LN=
G=20
import projects should be able to make money, analyst Benjamin Schlesinger=20
from Schlesinger and Associates said. But, if prices fall to $3.00 mmBtu, it=
=20
will be touch and go, Nimocks said.=20
With such bullish gas projections, companies are revamping existing LNG=20
terminals and building new ones. California, in particular, where roughly 40=
=20
percent of all electricity generation is derived from gas, would benefit fro=
m=20
LNG development.=20
Demand for gas in California, the second-largest U.S. market for gas and=20
10th-largest producing state, has outstripped the rate of local=20
infrastructure expansion. The resulting shortfall of gas supplies, plus a=20
lack of power plants, explain why the state is in a serious energy crisis.=20
NEW AND EXISTING TERMINALS=20
El Paso, the most ambitious of the LNG players, has plans for up to six new=20
terminals in Mexico, the Bahamas, and the United States, with the first of=20
two Mexican plants possibly on line in three years.=20
And both El Paso and Chevron are looking to bring supply from Australia as=20
high gas prices on the U.S West Coast make an alluring target for vast=20
Asia-Pacific gas resources.=20
BP has tentative plans to build up to three new terminals, with one in=20
Florida, and energy powerhouse Enron Corp. has proposed a plant in the=20
Bahamas connected by a 90-mile (145 km) pipeline to Florida.=20
The LNG terminal-building spree would expand or open up the U.S. market to=20
gas producers like Algeria, Trinidad, Nigeria and Qatar. Texaco, for its=20
planned facility in the Gulf of Mexico, plans to bring LNG from Angola.=20
Existing U.S. terminals are also in for a renaissance. Currently the country=
=20
has four LNG import terminals, but only two of them - one at Lake Charles,=20
La., the other at Everett, Mass., near Boston - are in operation. The other=20
two, in Cove Point, Md., and Elba Island, Ga., were idled years ago for lack=
=20
of demand but are expected to reopen in one to three years.=20
"The new LNG plants are not going to make LNG a big player, but they could=20
link natural gas prices in North America to the large supplies of gas=20
elsewhere in the world," Gruenspecht said.

